nt|^z@3^b@2|fp|3|cs|5|at|
^-{  Introduction and example deal 1 - The power of a trump suit  }
^-|fp||at|
Bridge is not the only trick-taking card game that uses a trump suit. If you have played games like euchre or spades, you already know quite a bit about the concept of trumps.

Even if you haven't played these games, you have heard the word trump before. Outside the world of cards you might hear someone say, "That's my trump card," to refer to a possession of great power or importance.|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|^^
That's exactly what the trump suit is in bridge - a suit of great power and importance. The bidding of a bridge deal determines which (if any) of the 4 suits will be the trump suit for that deal. The presence of a trump suit greatly influences the play of the cards and declarer's strategies for winning as many tricks as possible.

|cs|1|at|^-{Having lots of cards in the trump suit is a very good thing. The more 
trump cards the partnership holds, the more tricks they are likely to win.}

^-The bridge deals that we have seen so far did not contain a trump suit. In bridge we say that these deals were played in notrump. We are about to see a deal in which there is a trump suit. The trump suit for this deal is spades. The deal itself is not very realistic, but it is an example of just how powerful a trump suit can be.|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


qx|e1|
nt|^z@3^b@2|
cs|2|ht|d|fp|t|at|^-{ Example 1 - The power of a trump suit }
^-|fp||
%%%%%%%%%%%
cm|y|st||
md|sakqjt98d765432,hakqjtdakqjcakqj,s765432h5432c432|mb|7s|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|at|
We can see that spades are trump on this deal. North-South are lucky enough to have all 13 trumps between their 2 hands!|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
West, meanwhile, has been dealt a remarkable bridge hand. His 13 cards consist of 2 4-card solid suits (diamonds and clubs) plus a 5-card solid suit (hearts). It looks like West will be able to win all 13 tricks without breathing hard.|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
As you will see, however, the fact that spades are trump makes a dramatic difference to the trick-winning prospects of North-South and East-West. It doesn't matter which card West chooses for the opening lead. If West has any sense of the aesthetics of bridge, he will certainly choose the @H10.|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|ht|at|
Doesn't the rest of West's hand look pretty now that the @H10 is gone?

|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|at|
In ^*b face-to-face ^*n bridge dummy lays down his spades on the left. This is no accident.

|at|^-{It is traditional that dummy's trumps are layed down as the leftmost suit. 
When there is no trump suit, the dummy may arrange the suits as he sees fit.}|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cm||pc|h2|pc|h6|at|
The dummy and East both follow suit and it is South's turn to play. South doesn't have any hearts so he will have to find a discard. From what we have learned so far about bridge a discard can never win a trick. Suppose, however, that South chooses to discard a trump (remember, spades are trump). Watch what happens...|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s|
nt|^z@3^b@2
That's right - South won the trick even though he discarded. How is that possible?
^^|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{If a card from the trump suit is discarded, it can win the trick. Even the lowly
Two of the trump suit ranks higher than the Ace of one of the other suits!}|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
South's @S8 won trick 1 because spades are trump. West's @H10 would have won the trick if there was no trump suit. Since spades are trump on this deal, however, any spade that is played to a trick will beat any non-spade card.|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|at|
The presence of a trump suit does not change any other ^*Ibasic bridge rules^*N that we learned.
^^^-{Even if a deal has a trump suit, the players must follow suit to a trick if they can. North
could not have won the first trick by playing a trump - he had to follow suit with a heart.}|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|
Some trick-taking card games have rules that force players to trump in certain situations. Bridge does not have any rules along these lines.

^-{Players are not forced to play a trump if they cannot follow suit. They are
free to discard from another suit if they wish (but they won't win the trick).}|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
South, therefore, could have discarded a diamond (instead of a trump) on the first trick if he thought that was a good idea. South would have lost the first trick in that case to West's @H10. |
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
On this particular deal it would not have been smart for South to discard a diamond at trick 1. There are bridge deals, however, where declarer's correct strategy is to discard a non-trump even though a trump discard would win the trick.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|tc|r|at|
So South has won the first trick by trumping West's heart lead. Let's have a look at North-South's trick-winning prospects. South still has 6 solid spades in his hand. He could win the next 6 tricks by leading out his spades, 1 by 1.|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
South will win the first 7 tricks, but once their trumps are all gone there is no way that North-South will be able to win any more tricks. Can you see any way for North-South to win more than 7 tricks?|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|d|at|
Suppose South leads a diamond from his hand.|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|da|at|
West's diamonds are all equals. Suppose he decides to play his @DA to the second trick. Is there any way that North-South can meet this challenge and win the trick?|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s|at|
Well the dummy wasn't dealt any diamonds - the declarer must decide on a discard from the dummy. When declarer chooses to discard the @S2 from dummy, the power of having a trump suit really comes to light.|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|d|at|
East follows suit and the dummy wins the trick with the @S2! Even though West followed suit with the @DA, the @S2 was high enough to win the trick because spades are trump. Any trump card will beat any non-trump card in the battle for winning a trick.|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|c|pc|c|at|
Declarer continues with a club (or heart) lead from dummy and East follows suit.|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s|pc|ca|at|
South discards a trump and wins the trick as West, in frustration, follows suit with his @CA. All of West's clubs are equals so it doesn't matter which club he plays. How frustrating for West that none of his beautiful high clubs can win the trick once South has played a trump!|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Declarer will spend the next several tricks in this fashion, trumping South's diamonds in the dummy and trumping North's hearts and clubs in declarer's hand. Watch...|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


pc|d|pc|d|pc|s|pc|d|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


pc|h|pc|h|pc|s|pc|h|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


pc|d|pc|d|pc|s|pc|d|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


pc|c|pc|c|pc|s|pc|c|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


pc|d|pc|d|pc|s|
nt|^z@3^b@2
East is also out of diamonds by this time and therefore has to discard. If East had been dealt any trumps higher than dummy's @S5 he could overtrump and win the trick. Alas, East has no spades at all, so he must discard from another suit (and therefore cannot win the trick).|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|c|at|
East chooses to discard a club and the dummy's @S5 wins trick 8.|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|h|pc|h|pc|s|pc|h|at|
Declarer leads a heart from the dummy to trick 9 and wins the trick by trumping in the South hand. Do you notice anything unusual about the remaining position?|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
What's unusual is that South is the only player with diamonds remaining. South has already led diamonds 4 times, trumping each time in the dummy. All of the defenders'^*N diamonds were exhausted in the process. South's remaining diamonds have become winners in their own right!|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|d6|at|
When South leads the @D6, West must find a discard. West doesn't have any trumps to discard so there is no way he can win this trick.|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|c|at|
West chooses to discard a club and it is dummy's turn to play. The dummy could win this trick by playing a trump, but there is no need - South's @D6 is capable of winning the trick without any help from the dummy.|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|h|pc|c|at|
Declarer chooses to discard a heart from the dummy and East (who must really wish he had been dealt a spade) also discards. South's @D6 wins trick 10.|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|d|pc|h|pc|c|pc|c|at|
The next trick is similar. The @D7 is the last remaining diamond and it wins the trick as the other 3 players discard (once again North could win this trick by playing a trump).|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Declarer's last 2 cards are the @SA and @SK. Since spades are trump these 2 cards are the best 2 cards in the deck. The Ace of trumps must always win a trick. If the King of trumps is in the same hand as the trump Ace (as in this deal) it will always win a trick as well.

|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
North-South, therefore, win all 13 tricks! What a great advertisement for the power of trumps!|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
md|sakqjt98d765432,hakqjtdakqjcakqj,s765432h5432c432|mb|7s|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|at|
Let's have another look at all 52 cards of this deal. Notice, in particular, that North-South were dealt all 13 cards in the trump suit.|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Since North has no diamonds and South has no clubs or hearts, North-South can win all 13 tricks by trumping back and forth between the 2 hands. This procedure was not completely necessary as South's diamonds eventually became established as winners.|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Notice that West has all the high cards in the deck outside of spades. He would win the first 13 tricks at notrump, but he is unable to win a single trick when spades are trump!|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
You should know that this is a highly unusual bridge deal. Hands like South's (with cards in just 2 suits) and West's (with so many high cards) are extremely rare. Even the notion of one partnership being dealt all 13 trumps is something you don't see very often.|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|at|
Despite the fact that you are unlikely ever to see a bridge deal quite like this one when you are really playing, this deal vividly shows what trumps can do:|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


cs|1|at|^^
^-{Having lots of trumps between the partnership usually translates into 
lots of tricks, even more so when there are lots of short suits about.}|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
We have seen deals in which low cards in long suits can be established as tricks. This deal illustrates that short suits can also be an asset. Here North has a short suit in diamonds and South is short in both hearts and clubs. |
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The result is that the defenders cannot win any tricks in these suits - declarer will simply discard a trump from the appropriate hand.|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
