bt||cs|1|at|
^-{Trump Terminology}
^-
There are several useful words that bridge players use to describe plays involving the trump suit. The word trump itself can be used as either a noun, "I have lots of trump," or a verb, "I trumped West's lead in the dummy." The word ruff is often used instead of trump, "I ruffed West's lead in the dummy." We will soon see that there are also overruffs and underruffs in bridge.

|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


at|The 3 other suits (besides the trump suit) are referred so as side suits or off suits.  The deal we just saw is an example of a trick-taking technique known as a crossruff. In a crossruff ^*Ndeclarer^*N alternates between ruffing side suit cards in the dummy and in his own hand. We will have a closer look at the crossruff later in this chapter.

|
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


at|There are also some useful bridge terms for describing various ^*Ishort holdings^*N that a player might be dealt in a suit. When a player is dealt no cards at all in a particular suit he is said to be void in that suit. North had a diamond void on the previous deal, while South was void in both hearts and clubs. 

Being dealt just 1 card in a suit is referred to as being dealt a singleton in that suit, while a 2-card holding in a suit is known as a doubleton. "I was dealt a singleton diamond and a doubleton heart," is an example of how these terms are used.

|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


cs|2|at|If you think that it is not important to learn these bridge terms, consider this:

^-{Having names for various bridge situations and techniques is useful. Learning names makes
it easier to recognize situations and apply the right techniques when you are playing bridge.}
|
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The concept of the trump suit opens up a new world of possibilities as far as winning tricks is concerned. The best way to appreciate what a trump suit can do is to see it in action. Most of this chapter will consist of bridge deals in which the trump suit plays a starring role. Before we start, let's review what we have learned about the trump suit so far:

|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{The bidding determines which suit (if any) is the trump suit.
If there is no trump suit we say the deal is played in notrump.}

|
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


cs|2|at|{A player can win a trick by discarding from the trump suit (ruffing).
The highest trump card played to a trick will win the trick.}

|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


cs|3|at|{Even when there is a trump suit, you must always follow suit if you can!}

|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


cs|1|at|{If you cannot follow suit you are not required to discard a trump.
You are free to discard whatever you want. You do not have to ruff.}

|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


cs|4|at|{There are no special rules about leads in the trump suit itself. Any player
can lead trump at any time. You must follow suit if you can when trump is led.}

|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


cs|2|at|{^*IThe more the merrier^*N applies to the trump suit. The more
trumps a partnership has the more tricks they rate to be able to win.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


at|There is a great deal more to be learned about the trump suit in the deals that follow. 
Happy trumping!|
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


