nt|^z@3^b@2|st||
md|skqjthaq5432dakc2,sa987hjtdjcjt9876,s5432hK6d65432ca3|mb|6h|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|sk|s|
cs|2|ht|d|fp|t|at|^-{Example 2 - Drawing trump}
^-|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|fp||at|
On this deal hearts is the trump suit. We have 6 trumps including the Ace and Queen.|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|dj|at|
West's opening lead is the @DJ and dummy puts down some useful cards - the @CA and the @HK. Kings are always nice cards, but the King of trumps is something special. It is the second most powerful card in the deck!|
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
You should also appreciate dummy's @H6. We will not win a trick with this card, but the more trumps the merrier! Be happy that dummy has the @H6 instead of one of the defenders.

|
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


pc|d2|pc|d7|pc|dk|
nt|^z@3^b@2
The first trick is not very interesting as we win West's diamond lead in the South hand.|
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Look at South's spades. They are solid except for the @SA and we can develop 3 extra tricks by driving out that card. If this was a notrump deal that might be a good strategy.|
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Playing on spades is not such a good idea when hearts are trump. Watch...|
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|sk|at|
We play the @SK out of our hand in an attempt to drive out the @SA.|
pg| ***** 66 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|sa|pc|s2|pc|s6|at|
West wins the @SA leaving the South hand with 3 certain spade winners.|
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Unfortunately, things are not always certain when a trump suit is involved. Can you see the danger that we have put ourselves in?|
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s9|at|
Suppose West returns a spade. Are you thinking, "No problem, we have all of the remaining high spades?" Well, there just might be a problem...|
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s3|pc|h7|at|
Dummy follows suit with a small spade and East ruffs!|
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
One of those high spades is not going to take a trick after all. We have to follow suit with one of the spade cards we were hoping to win a trick with.|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|st|
nt|^z@3^b@2
East has just robbed us of one of our ^*Icertain tricks^*N by trumping his partner's spade lead. That's bad news and it is about to get worse!|
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|dq|at|
East returns the @DQ. It looks like we will win this trick with the @DA, another ^*Icertain winner^*N, but you probably know what is about to happen!|
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|da|pc|ht|pc|d3|at|
West is now void in diamonds and he ruffs our @DA. Another certain winner goes down the drain! Care to predict what the next trick will look like?|
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s7|pc|s4|pc|h8|pc|sj|at|
West leads another spade and East ruffs yet another trick we were hoping to win. It is beginning to appear that the concept of a trump suit is very overrated!|
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


sk||
nt|^z@3^b@2
The next trick is going to be interesting so let's have a look at the remaining cards.|
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|dt|at|
East leads another diamond and South cannot follow suit. This looks like a chance for the trump suit to work in our favor for a change! We can ruff East's diamond lead and win the trick.|
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|h2|at|
Something bad is going to happen, however, if we ruff with one of our small trumps.|
pg| ***** 78 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|hj|pc|d4|at|
West is able to overruff and win the trick. Unlike some trick-taking games you are not obligated to overruff at bridge. West was allowed to discard from another suit if he wanted to, but overruffing was a good idea on this particular trick! The next trick will be especially demoralizing...|
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|s8|pc|s5|pc|h9|pc|sq|at|
West returns his last spade and East ruffs with his last trump. We end up winning no spade tricks at all. That is a real shame given the promising spade holding we were dealt (the @SKQJ10).|
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
We have lost 6 tricks, the @SA and 5 ruffs by the defenders. North-South began with 8 trumps between the 2 hands (South was dealt 6 hearts but he has ruffed once).|
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
That means the defenders won tricks with all 5 of the trumps they were originally dealt. That's pretty good
defending!|
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
North-South will be able to win the last 7 tricks (for a total of 8 tricks). South can ruff East's next diamond return without fear of being overruffed again - the defenders are out of trump. Dummy has the @CA to take care of South's @C2.|
pg| ***** 83 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Not to take anything away from the defenders, who really played some great bridge there, but we could have done much better as declarer. Remember, we won only 7 tricks in our first try.|
pg| ***** 84 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Let's back up to the point where we had our first chance to ruff.|
pg| ***** 85 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|up||up||up||up||up||up||up||at|
East has just led a diamond and the South hand is void. The last time we were in this position we ruffed with the @H2 and West overruffed with the @HJ to win the trick.|
pg| ***** 86 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|ha|
nt|^z@3^b@2
Suppose that we decide to ruff with the @HA instead of the @H2. Nothing beats the Ace of trump so we don't have to worry about getting overruffed on this trick.|
pg| ***** 87 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
West could, of course, choose to underruff with his @HJ. However, It is usually a bad idea to underruff. Save your trumps for later and discard from another suit if you cannot overruff.|
pg| ***** 88 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
nt|^z@3^b@2|pc|c6|pc|d4|at|
On this deal it wouldn't actually hurt West to underruff, but he wisely chooses to discard instead, hoping that the @HJ might win a future trick.|
pg| ***** 89 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Can you see how we can play to make sure there are no future tricks for the defenders?|
